Rmarkdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com and be sure to download the Rmarkdown Cheatsheet developed by Rstudio. A more detailed reference guide to Rmarkdown can be obtained here

Rmarkdown is run on a package called knitr(). knitr() is a powerful tool for creating reports and summaries of your quantiative research, and it is an important part of a reproducible research toolbox. The knitr package was developed by Yihui Xie a statistics Ph.D. who now works at Rstudio. The value of reproducible research especially in the process of data exploration and visualization is immense. There are tons of powerful ways you can use the knitr() package to increase your efficiency and produce amazing output from your analyses. During this course we will continually build on the capabilities of rmarkdown. But for today we are simply going to get comfortable with the primary reproducible research tool for R which is the knitr package.

Since many of you are using Rstudio you will benefit from the tight integration which the Rstudio interface has with the knitr package. For instance in the toolbar above the text editor quadrant of the Rstudio interface you will see a “Knit” button. That essentially executes the knitr::render() function in the background allowing the user to create reports and package output without having to execute commands in the R console. A great resource for more details on the knitr package is knitr in a knutshell by Karl Browman, or for a longer exposition you could read Dynamic Documents with R and knitr.

Questions

  1. Anscombes quartet is a set of 4 \(x,y\) data sets that were published by Francis Anscombe in a 1973 paper Graphs in statistical analysis. For this first question load the anscombe data that is part of the library(datasets) in R. And assign that data to a new object called data.
data <- anscombe
  1. Summarise the data by calculating the mean, variance, for each column and the correlation between each pair (eg. x1 and y1, x2 and y2, etc) (Hint: use the fBasics() package!)
cat("mean of column 1 to 8")
## mean of column 1 to 8
data %>% 
    group_by() %>% 
    summarise_each(funs(mean)) %>% 
    select(mean_ = everything()) %>% kable()
mean_1 mean_2 mean_3 mean_4 mean_5 mean_6 mean_7 mean_8
9 9 9 9 7.500909 7.500909 7.5 7.500909 
cat("variance of column 1 to 8")
## variance of column 1 to 8
data %>% 
    group_by() %>% 
    summarise_each(funs(var)) %>% 
    select(var_ = everything()) %>% kable()
var_1 var_2 var_3 var_4 var_5 var_6 var_7 var_8
11 11 11 11 4.127269 4.127629 4.12262 4.123249

Before calculating the pairwise (aligned on position) correlation, notice that data is clearly not tidy data, there is one dimension, factor 1:4, clearly hidden in the column name. Thus, before we do anything further, restructure data to a tidy data set, for easier loop in regression, easier plotting too.

data[,1:4] %>% 
    gather("num", "x", 1:4) %>% 
    mutate(num = str_sub(num, 2), id = 1:44) %>% 
    inner_join(
        data[,5:8] %>% 
            gather("num", "y", 1:4) %>% 
            mutate(num = str_sub(num, 2), id = 1:44)
    ) %>% 
    select(-id) -> data
## Joining, by = c("num", "id")
data %>% head() %>% kable()
num x y
1 10 8.04
1 8 6.95
1 13 7.58
1 9 8.81
1 11 8.33
1 14 9.96

Looking good! Now we run pair wise correlation for every num with ease.

data %>% 
    group_by(num) %>% 
    summarise(corr_xy = cor(x,y)) %>% kable()
num corr_xy
1 0.8164205
2 0.8162365
3 0.8162867
4 0.8165214

Notice they are almost the same.

  1. Create scatter plots for each \(x, y\) pair of data.
data %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x, y)) + 
    geom_point(colour = "#004D43", size = 2.5, alpha = 0.7) + 
    facet_grid(. ~ num)

  1. Now change the symbols on the scatter plots to solid circles and plot them together as a 4 panel graphic

This is actually done through last step, already solid dots.

  1. Now fit a linear model to each data set using the lm() function.

  2. Now combine the last two tasks. Create a four panel scatter plot matrix that has both the data points and the regression lines. (hint: the model objects will carry over chunks!)

This two steps could be completed in one ggplot call.

data %>% 
    ggplot(aes(x, y)) + 
    geom_point(colour = "#004D43", size = 2.5, alpha = 0.8) + 
    stat_smooth(method = 'lm', size = 1) + 
    facet_grid(. ~ num)

  1. Now compare the model fits for each model object.

The models are the same

for (i in unique(data$num)) {
    fit = lm(y ~ x, data[data$num == i, ])
    print(fit$coefficients)
}

  1. In text, summarize the lesson of Anscombe’s Quartet and what it says about the value of data visualization.

Anscombe data set demonstrate that data viz can reveal the relationship in the data that’s not visible. This is a good example of Tufte’s concept of Graphiccal Excellence.
